WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.120
I'm here to talk about AI and Shiny for Python.

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:13.440
Now as I was working on my talk, I actually realized that it would be better to talk about

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:19.680
AI, and specifically large language models, and how they fit in with systems, you know,

00:00:19.680 --> 00:00:25.840
larger systems with humans and other computer programs, and sort of put Shiny in a supporting

00:00:25.840 --> 00:00:28.400
role for that.

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:31.480
So and when I talk about, again, when I talk about AI, I'm referring to large language

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:36.439
models, and when I talk about large language models, I'm mostly referring to the ones by

00:00:36.439 --> 00:00:41.439
Open API, or Open AI, I'm sorry, which is, you know, those are the best known by far

00:00:41.439 --> 00:00:43.919
and probably the most commonly used.

00:00:43.919 --> 00:00:48.000
All right, so what is a large language model?

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.119
Well there's a lot of different levels that you can look at this question.

00:00:54.119 --> 00:00:58.720
So at one level, it's a neural network, and a neural network involves a lot of matrix

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:00.360
math.

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:06.839
So there's a quote by Simon Willison, who's somebody who thinks about this stuff a lot

00:01:06.839 --> 00:01:07.839
on his website.

00:01:07.839 --> 00:01:12.320
These things are giant binary blobs of numbers, anything you can do with them, anything you

00:01:12.320 --> 00:01:17.360
do with them involves vast amounts of matrix multiplication, that's it.

00:01:17.360 --> 00:01:22.519
It's an opaque blob that can do weird and interesting things.

00:01:22.519 --> 00:01:24.000
So that's one level.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:29.800
Another level is that they are statistical models, they make predictions, and the things

00:01:29.800 --> 00:01:31.720
they predict are text.

00:01:31.720 --> 00:01:36.080
You give it text, and it'll predict what the next word should be in that text.

00:01:36.080 --> 00:01:42.800
So in a way, it's similar to the, you know, the keyboard on your mobile phone.

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:46.800
You write in some stuff there, so if I've written, I would like a, then it gives me

00:01:46.800 --> 00:01:51.800
some possible next words, and in this case, it's glass, coffee, and cheeseburger.

00:01:52.519 --> 00:01:56.720
Now, the model that's used on your phone is gonna be way simpler than these large language

00:01:56.720 --> 00:02:00.480
models that do the really interesting stuff.

00:02:00.480 --> 00:02:05.160
One other thing to know about them is that we don't really understand how they think.

00:02:05.160 --> 00:02:08.960
This was actually really kind of confusing for me at first, it took me a while to really

00:02:08.960 --> 00:02:13.360
internalize this, but we understand how they work at a low level, but at a higher level,

00:02:13.360 --> 00:02:17.880
we don't know how they conceptualize a chair, or anything like that.

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:21.080
It's still sort of a mystery.

00:02:22.080 --> 00:02:28.800
All right, now, I showed you text prediction, and we're all familiar with ChatGPT, so one

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:33.360
question you might have is, how do you create a conversation with word prediction?

00:02:33.360 --> 00:02:36.960
How do you, you know, if I'm just predicting the next word in the string, like, how does

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:41.880
it work when there's a back and forth between two people?

00:02:41.880 --> 00:02:44.679
So it's actually pretty simple.

00:02:44.679 --> 00:02:49.479
There's the input, and it looks something like this, so there's a string here, and I

00:02:49.479 --> 00:02:55.080
say, user colon, why is the sky blue?

00:02:55.080 --> 00:02:58.639
And then I continue the string, and the next line I say, assistant colon, and then I close

00:02:58.639 --> 00:02:59.639
the string.

00:02:59.639 --> 00:03:06.479
And so you give that to the model, and it will return an output that looks like this.

00:03:06.479 --> 00:03:09.000
The sky appears blue because dot dot dot.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:15.559
So really, what I've done is I've prompted it to, you know, to take part in a dialogue,

00:03:15.559 --> 00:03:16.880
and it knows how to fill in the rest of it.

00:03:16.880 --> 00:03:22.000
So that's how it does it with this word prediction.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.479
So this sort of chat interface has been really enormously successful.

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:26.960
I mean, we all know about ChatGPT.

00:03:26.960 --> 00:03:31.479
And I did some work earlier this year on a Python package called ChatString, which you

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:33.600
can use to make AI chat apps with Shiny.

00:03:33.600 --> 00:03:37.919
So I'm going to show you a really basic app made with this.

00:03:37.919 --> 00:03:41.639
All right, so this is basically like ChatGPT.

00:03:41.639 --> 00:03:43.839
You know, you can type in your question.

00:03:43.839 --> 00:03:46.160
So why is the sky blue?

00:03:46.160 --> 00:03:47.160
And it gives you an answer.

00:03:47.160 --> 00:03:48.160
And why not red?

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:50.880
And it gives you another answer.

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:55.639
And it does that by talking to the OpenAI API.

00:03:55.639 --> 00:03:57.639
That's how it gets those answers.

00:03:57.639 --> 00:04:02.479
And to create an application like this, this particular application, it's really simple.

00:04:02.479 --> 00:04:05.600
So we've got the normal Shiny stuff there.

00:04:05.600 --> 00:04:08.520
There's a UI and server parts of the app.

00:04:08.520 --> 00:04:14.080
And then we say ChatStream.chatUI, and you give it an ID, in this case, my chat.

00:04:14.080 --> 00:04:18.640
And then in the server part, we say ChatStream.chatServer, my chat.

00:04:18.640 --> 00:04:20.000
And then that's all you need to do.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:22.079
Well, and you need to get an API key.

00:04:22.079 --> 00:04:25.880
But those are things you need to do to make that simple application.

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:33.040
OK, now, before we do more interesting things with this, it will be useful to sort of understand

00:04:33.040 --> 00:04:36.640
how it talks to the OpenAI API.

00:04:36.640 --> 00:04:41.239
So when you ask it a question, it makes a request to the API.

00:04:41.239 --> 00:04:45.940
And that request is just some JSON text, or JSON that contains some text.

00:04:45.940 --> 00:04:52.739
So it has this part of the message that says, roll system, content, you are a helpful system.

00:04:52.739 --> 00:04:55.140
That is the system prompt.

00:04:55.140 --> 00:04:58.640
And that's not something that most users interact with.

00:04:58.640 --> 00:05:01.519
That's just sort of usually hidden.

00:05:01.519 --> 00:05:04.640
And then there is the actual question.

00:05:04.640 --> 00:05:05.640
Roll user.

00:05:05.640 --> 00:05:06.640
Why is the sky blue?

00:05:06.640 --> 00:05:09.480
All right, so it sends that message over to the API.

00:05:09.480 --> 00:05:10.480
And then it gets a response.

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:16.480
And the response comes back, roll assistant, content, and there's an answer that the LLM

00:05:16.480 --> 00:05:17.480
has generated.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:22.959
Now, to turn this into a conversation, we make another request.

00:05:22.959 --> 00:05:29.920
So just so you know, on their servers, they don't record, well, they don't keep track

00:05:29.920 --> 00:05:31.279
of the state of this conversation.

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:32.279
It's stateless.

00:05:32.279 --> 00:05:33.799
They actually do record this stuff.

00:05:33.799 --> 00:05:37.679
So for reasons, I guess.

00:05:37.679 --> 00:05:40.440
Anyway, so we make another request.

00:05:40.440 --> 00:05:42.920
And we include the previous information that we had.

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:47.799
And then we also tack onto it the reply that it gave us to us earlier.

00:05:47.799 --> 00:05:49.119
And then we can ask our next question.

00:05:49.119 --> 00:05:52.880
All right, so roll user, content, why not red?

00:05:52.880 --> 00:05:54.720
And then it sends another response.

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.160
All right, so this is how a conversation works.

00:05:57.160 --> 00:06:01.640
So every time I add something to the conversation, I'm actually, I have to send it the whole

00:06:01.640 --> 00:06:03.399
previous conversation.

00:06:03.399 --> 00:06:11.079
All right, now, one other interesting thing about this was that system prompt.

00:06:11.079 --> 00:06:13.320
So you hear a lot about prompt engineering.

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:18.920
I put it in quotes because it seems like kind of, that seems a little bit like an exaggeration

00:06:18.920 --> 00:06:19.959
calling engineering.

00:06:19.959 --> 00:06:25.359
But you can change that to change the behavior of the responses that it gives you.

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:32.640
So we can give it this prompt, like, role system content, you are a sarcastic teenager.

00:06:32.640 --> 00:06:37.040
And if you're using chat stream, you can just pass it in as an argument to the chat server

00:06:37.040 --> 00:06:39.640
function.

00:06:39.640 --> 00:06:42.600
And so now when you ask it, why is the sky blue, it'll say, oh, I don't know, maybe because

00:06:42.600 --> 00:06:45.359
it's too cool to be another color.

00:06:45.359 --> 00:06:52.200
All right, all right, so I'm going to go to show you some more examples of this, of using

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:53.200
chat stream.

00:06:53.519 --> 00:07:00.320
First, I want to talk a little bit about how LLMs fit into systems that you might build.

00:07:00.320 --> 00:07:05.519
So in these systems, you know, with humans and computers, well, there's obviously humans.

00:07:05.519 --> 00:07:09.040
So humans can do many different things.

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:13.679
But we have unpredictable behavior, and we easily get tired and bored.

00:07:13.679 --> 00:07:15.559
And I know that's especially true for me.

00:07:15.559 --> 00:07:19.160
Then we have computer programs, which are really good at doing the things that they're

00:07:19.160 --> 00:07:21.480
specifically designed to do.

00:07:21.480 --> 00:07:26.959
They have very predictable behavior, and they never get tired or bored.

00:07:26.959 --> 00:07:31.880
And then we also have LLMs, which obviously are computer programs, but I'm going to categorize

00:07:31.880 --> 00:07:34.119
them differently here.

00:07:34.119 --> 00:07:37.920
They can do many things, and it's often surprising what they can do.

00:07:37.920 --> 00:07:39.420
The behavior is trained.

00:07:39.420 --> 00:07:42.160
It's not designed.

00:07:42.160 --> 00:07:45.200
And the behavior is not completely predictable.

00:07:45.200 --> 00:07:50.839
And like regular computer programs, though, they also never get tired or bored.

00:07:50.880 --> 00:07:55.079
So with all that in mind, let's look at a practical use case.

00:07:55.079 --> 00:08:02.760
So I sometimes look for recipes on the internet, and I Google them, and I end up at websites

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:03.760
like this.

00:08:03.760 --> 00:08:04.760
All right.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:09.200
So this is real deal sesame noodles.

00:08:09.200 --> 00:08:12.640
And so you go to a web page like this.

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:18.040
There's some text at the beginning, some beautiful pictures, some text, sesame noodles, a symphony

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:25.160
of flavor, advertisements, pictures, a lot of ingredients, very easy to make.

00:08:25.160 --> 00:08:27.559
Pop-up advertisement.

00:08:27.559 --> 00:08:30.399
The sesame noodle sauce isn't just for noodles.

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:31.399
More pictures.

00:08:31.399 --> 00:08:33.280
Make your own chili oil if you can.

00:08:33.280 --> 00:08:34.280
How to serve sesame noodles.

00:08:34.280 --> 00:08:36.400
Better too much sauce than too little.

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:37.400
All right.

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:38.919
So it's a lot of this stuff.

00:08:38.919 --> 00:08:40.239
More pictures.

00:08:40.239 --> 00:08:46.359
And then finally, we get down to here, where the recipe is.

00:08:46.400 --> 00:08:50.080
Now, suppose you want to take this information and put it in a database.

00:08:50.080 --> 00:08:54.400
Like I want to keep track of some recipes that I like.

00:08:54.400 --> 00:09:01.200
Well, that's converting, that would be converting unstructured data to structured data.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:09.479
So taking that website and turning it into a format that you can put into a database.

00:09:09.479 --> 00:09:13.039
Now computer programs aren't very good at this, because the input is too messy.

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:17.799
Maybe I could write something that could extract the recipe out of that particular website.

00:09:17.799 --> 00:09:21.000
But if I just sent it to some arbitrary other website, it would completely fail and I'd

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:24.559
have to write a new program to do that.

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:29.799
People aren't good at that, because it's too boring.

00:09:29.799 --> 00:09:32.760
But it turns out that LLMs are very good at this.

00:09:32.760 --> 00:09:37.080
And it's almost magic how good they are at doing these sorts of things.

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:41.799
So if we build an application to do this for us, we have a few components.

00:09:41.799 --> 00:09:46.960
So first, there's the web interface to make it easy for the human to interact.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:51.080
Then we have Python to do the computery stuff like fetching the web page and scraping text,

00:09:51.080 --> 00:09:55.840
and also running the web server for the Shiny app and all that.

00:09:55.840 --> 00:10:00.359
And we also have an LLM, which takes the unstructured text and will synthesize the structured data

00:10:00.359 --> 00:10:01.520
out of it.

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:06.599
So let's take a look at how a program like this would work in practice.

00:10:06.599 --> 00:10:11.320
So we could enter in the recipe URL.

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:18.559
And this is the LLM returning to us the recipe in JSON format, which then we can do something

00:10:18.559 --> 00:10:21.239
with, like put it in a database.

00:10:21.239 --> 00:10:28.000
Now there is one more thing in here that I sort of glossed over, which is the prompt.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:32.359
So it's not like I just gave it a URL and it magically did this.

00:10:32.359 --> 00:10:36.640
I did have to give it a little bit of a hint of what it should be doing with the URL.

00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:39.919
So sorry, with the text that I got from the URL.

00:10:39.919 --> 00:10:43.440
So this is the system prompt that I used for this application.

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:47.799
Your goal is to extract recipe content from text and return a JSON representation of the

00:10:47.799 --> 00:10:48.799
useful information.

00:10:48.799 --> 00:10:51.200
The JSON should be structured like this.

00:10:51.200 --> 00:10:52.200
And then I give it an example.

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:53.200
All right.

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:55.400
And that example is very helpful.

00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:57.520
It's very important so that it'll give me the right thing.

00:10:57.520 --> 00:10:59.760
So I gave it that example.

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:04.039
And then this is the output that it returned, which is structured in just exactly the same

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:05.039
way.

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:06.039
And it's actually cool.

00:11:06.039 --> 00:11:11.840
It adds some extra things in there, like it's at the very bottom of the slide, added tags.

00:11:11.840 --> 00:11:12.840
It's a side.

00:11:12.840 --> 00:11:14.280
And I can't remember what else.

00:11:14.280 --> 00:11:19.599
So that if you want to search for it in the database, you could do that, even though those

00:11:19.599 --> 00:11:22.919
things weren't present in the original web page.

00:11:22.919 --> 00:11:26.559
It just figured that out because it knows something about sesame noodles.

00:11:27.080 --> 00:11:28.080
OK.

00:11:28.080 --> 00:11:33.599
So that's really useful, having this structured data.

00:11:33.599 --> 00:11:37.760
But you might find that you need to validate the output from the LLM.

00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:45.400
So as I said earlier, the LLM output is not completely predictable.

00:11:45.400 --> 00:11:46.400
Like if I sent it to...

00:11:46.400 --> 00:11:49.239
I mean, it worked for that particular recipe.

00:11:49.239 --> 00:11:53.520
But if I sent it to another website or got another recipe, it might mess it up somehow.

00:11:53.520 --> 00:11:55.840
You can't be completely sure that it's going to do the right thing.

00:11:55.840 --> 00:11:58.679
That's one of the annoying things about them.

00:11:58.679 --> 00:12:03.000
But we can use a human to validate the output.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:09.159
The problem with that is that reading the JSON is hard and it's boring.

00:12:09.159 --> 00:12:13.239
But fortunately, we can use the computer to do computery things to make the structured

00:12:13.239 --> 00:12:14.760
data easier for human consumption.

00:12:14.760 --> 00:12:15.760
All right.

00:12:15.760 --> 00:12:20.280
So let me show you what this application would look like.

00:12:20.280 --> 00:12:22.880
We'll enter in that recipe URL again.

00:12:22.919 --> 00:12:30.280
But this time, when we render it, we have Shiny taking that JSON and rendering it into

00:12:30.280 --> 00:12:33.520
HTML so that it's easier for us to look at.

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:37.559
So we can look at that and inspect it and say, hey, this looks like a proper recipe.

00:12:37.559 --> 00:12:38.919
It looks correct.

00:12:38.919 --> 00:12:43.919
And then after the human inspects it, then we can continue and say, click on Add Recipe

00:12:43.919 --> 00:12:46.719
and add that to our database.

00:12:46.719 --> 00:12:49.520
All right.

00:12:50.239 --> 00:12:51.239
OK.

00:12:51.239 --> 00:12:54.679
Another thing that you might want to do is augment the knowledge of your large language

00:12:54.679 --> 00:12:55.679
model.

00:12:55.679 --> 00:13:03.320
So for OpenAI, I believe their knowledge cutoff dates are in the beginning of 2022 now.

00:13:03.320 --> 00:13:05.479
So for example, they don't know anything about Shiny for Python.

00:13:05.479 --> 00:13:11.559
If you ask it about Shiny for Python and ask it to generate an app, it'll just hallucinate

00:13:11.559 --> 00:13:16.520
something or it'll give you a Streamlet app or a Dash app.

00:13:16.520 --> 00:13:25.200
But we do have a lot of Shiny for Python documentation, which you can actually give it to the large

00:13:25.200 --> 00:13:26.640
language model.

00:13:26.640 --> 00:13:30.239
So in order to do that, I'll sort of go over the procedure here.

00:13:30.239 --> 00:13:34.479
So you can have a computer break up the document into text pieces and store them in a vector

00:13:34.479 --> 00:13:35.479
database.

00:13:35.479 --> 00:13:40.080
And unfortunately, I don't have time to go into how the vector database works.

00:13:40.080 --> 00:13:43.119
But you'll store them in the vector database.

00:13:43.119 --> 00:13:50.359
So then when a human asks a question about the document or our documents, the computer

00:13:50.359 --> 00:13:56.280
can use the vector database and extract possibly relevant pieces of text.

00:13:56.280 --> 00:13:58.080
It's a probabilistic thing.

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:03.200
It'll extract pieces of text that it thinks are probably relevant and just sort of sticks

00:14:03.200 --> 00:14:08.000
those all together, all those pieces of text together, and send them to the LLM along with

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:10.440
the question.

00:14:10.440 --> 00:14:15.359
So then the LLM ingests that text and synthesizes something useful for the human.

00:14:15.359 --> 00:14:21.159
So if my question is, show me how to build a basic Shiny for Python application, from

00:14:21.159 --> 00:14:24.840
the vector database, it might extract all these pieces of text.

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:26.799
You don't have to read them.

00:14:26.799 --> 00:14:28.700
But these are just chunks of text.

00:14:28.700 --> 00:14:31.880
And some of them are relevant and some of them might not be.

00:14:31.880 --> 00:14:34.599
And they all get sent to the large language model.

00:14:34.599 --> 00:14:38.840
So let's see this in action.

00:14:38.840 --> 00:14:43.359
So show me how to create a basic Shiny for Python application.

00:14:43.359 --> 00:14:45.400
And there it is.

00:14:45.400 --> 00:14:51.000
It's returned the code for a basic Shiny for Python app, which, again, the GPT models don't

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.440
actually know about them.

00:14:53.440 --> 00:14:58.960
They're only informed about them from this information that we just sent it.

00:14:58.960 --> 00:15:03.419
I can ask, how do I deploy this application to PositConnect?

00:15:03.419 --> 00:15:07.280
And then it provides that information as well.

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:11.880
So one thing I want to point out is that, in this particular app, you can see that there's

00:15:11.880 --> 00:15:13.520
a model dropdown selector.

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:17.000
It's using GPT 3.5 Turbo 16k.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:21.400
The 16k means that's the amount of tokens it can take for the context.

00:15:21.400 --> 00:15:24.280
That means the default is 4k.

00:15:24.280 --> 00:15:27.239
The 16k means you can provide it with a lot more information, which is really useful when

00:15:27.239 --> 00:15:28.239
you're doing this.

00:15:28.239 --> 00:15:33.159
Because those pieces of text that are sent over are, again, they're not necessarily relevant.

00:15:33.159 --> 00:15:34.159
They're probably relevant.

00:15:34.159 --> 00:15:37.000
So throwing more of them in there is helpful.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.799
All right.

00:15:38.799 --> 00:15:40.799
So some takeaways.

00:15:40.799 --> 00:15:42.760
This is the last slide.

00:15:42.760 --> 00:15:46.919
So humans, normal computer programs, and LLMs are good at different things.

00:15:46.919 --> 00:15:51.719
And we can combine them together to play to their strengths.

00:15:51.719 --> 00:15:56.559
And when it comes to Shiny, Shiny is a useful bridge between human and computer programs.

00:15:56.559 --> 00:16:00.599
And chat stream can help you build AI chat apps with Shiny.

00:16:00.599 --> 00:16:01.599
So thanks.

00:16:02.039 --> 00:16:09.760
Thank you so much.

00:16:09.760 --> 00:16:11.599
We have time for a few questions.

00:16:11.599 --> 00:16:14.479
The first one is, can you run this app on Shiny Live?

00:16:14.479 --> 00:16:15.479
Yes.

00:16:15.479 --> 00:16:22.919
Well, so there is a version of chat stream where I sort of had to hack it to get it to

00:16:22.919 --> 00:16:25.799
talk to the OpenAI API.

00:16:25.799 --> 00:16:30.119
But then you also have to have your API key sent along with the Shiny Live application.

00:16:30.119 --> 00:16:36.200
So whoever's running that Shiny Live application will have your OpenAI API key, which is probably

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:37.200
not a good idea.

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:40.119
But, I mean, if you trust them, if it's for something internal, maybe that could work.

00:16:40.119 --> 00:16:44.799
But again, that was also a special, like, weird version of chat stream that I'm not

00:16:44.799 --> 00:16:46.719
sure I have on a branch yet.

00:16:46.719 --> 00:16:48.960
But I have code for it somewhere.

00:16:48.960 --> 00:16:55.239
Next, can we leverage different LLMs available, such as Llama2, instead of the OpenAI API

00:16:55.239 --> 00:16:58.960
in chat stream?

00:16:58.960 --> 00:16:59.960
Currently no.

00:17:00.799 --> 00:17:05.599
Getting that to work would be pretty straightforward, because the API communication is pretty simple.

00:17:05.599 --> 00:17:08.880
You just, you know, you send it a JSON message, and it sends you something back.

00:17:08.880 --> 00:17:10.719
And there is a streaming aspect of it.

00:17:10.719 --> 00:17:17.319
So I think it probably would not be too hard to modularize the Llama2 protocol.

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:21.239
But I have not tried it before, so I can't say that for sure.

00:17:21.239 --> 00:17:23.079
And last question.

00:17:23.079 --> 00:17:28.359
Can chat stream output be other content, such as plots?

00:17:28.760 --> 00:17:34.599
Well, no, it can't, because OpenAI will just give you text.

00:17:34.599 --> 00:17:36.560
So it doesn't do plots.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:41.280
Although, well, you could run some code from them to generate plots and then render those

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:42.280
using Shiny.

00:17:42.280 --> 00:17:45.719
I know George has experimented with that a little bit.

00:17:45.719 --> 00:17:52.959
But I can't say too much about that now, because it's just an experimental thing.

00:17:52.959 --> 00:17:53.959
Thank you so much.

00:17:53.959 --> 00:17:54.959
This was Winston.

00:17:54.959 --> 00:17:55.959
Great.

00:17:55.959 --> 00:17:56.959
Thank you.

00:17:56.959 --> 00:17:56.959


